The article discusses the Partnerships for Opportunity and Workforce and Economic Revitalization (POWER) Initiative, which aims to help communities negatively impacted by changes in the coal industry and power sector. The initiative involves multiple federal agencies and will provide grants to communities to develop comprehensive strategic plans and execute economic and workforce development activities. The grants will be awarded on two tracks: planning grants for communities without existing economic development plans, and implementation grants for communities that have already done strategic planning. The article also outlines the funding sources and administrative structure of the POWER initiative, as well as the eligibility criteria for applicants. The timeline for the initiative is also provided.